observations.recommendation:
We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to instruct the:
a. Inventory Committee to (i) conduct a complete physical inventory and submit the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment to the office of the Audit Team not later than January 31 of each year; and (ii) ensure the proper tagging of all properties and adopt a standardized system of property numbering;
b. GSO-designate to (i) maintain Property Cards based on source documents, such as Purchase Orders, Delivery Receipts/Invoices, and Inspection and Acceptance Reports, ensuring that all required details are accurately and completely recorded for each type of property; and (ii) maintain Local Road Inventory and Road Map and Local Road Network Property Card;
c. Municipal Accountant to (i) prepare and maintain Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Card (PPELC), Construction-in-Progress Ledger Cards (CIPLC) and Real Property Ledger Cards (RPLC); and (ii) draw the necessary journal entry voucher/s to reflect the adjustments of misclassified PPEs;
d. Municipal Engineering Office to provide the Municipal Accountant and the GSO-designate the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects using the prescribed format as basis of the Municipal Accountant to recognize the same in the books of accounts and the GSO-designate to complete his property records; and
e. Municipal Assessor to fast track the necessary actions for the registration and titling of the remaining landholdings.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to instruct the:
(a) Municipal Engineer, being the building official, to inform all applicants of building permits of their responsibilities after the completion of the structure, which include, among others, the filing of a sworn declaration of the true value of the structure. Likewise, inspect properties applied for building permits that have not yet been applied for an occupancy permit and compel the owner to perform their duties mandated by the law;
(b) Municipal Assessor to verify the status of undeclared property and henceforth declare the same in the name of the defaulting owner, if known, or against an unknown owner, as the case may be, and assess the property for taxation in accordance with laws, rules and regulations;
(c) Municipal Treasurer to (i) regularly prepare and issue the necessary notice of delinquency and demand letters to delinquent taxpayers; and (ii) post the notice of the delinquency at the main entrance hall and in a publicly accessible and conspicuous place in each barangay of the municipality where the property is located; and
d) Municipal Accountant to draw a journal entry voucher to recognize the correcting entries on the understated property tax receivable accounts.

We recommended and Local Chief Executive agreed that:
a. The Municipal Treasurer
i. Prioritize the finalization of the stratified schedule of presumptive income level based on industry classifications, business size, location, and other relevant operational indicators to approximate the gross receipts of each business classification for every tax period. Once established, it may serve as a standard reference in estimating gross sales or receipts for businesses that fail to provide sufficient documentation;
ii. Require all persons, who are granted a permit to conduct an activity or business and who are liable, to pay the business tax to submit a certified photocopy of their income tax returns (ITR) on or before April 30 of each year and collect any tax deficiency, if any, including interest at the rate of ten percent (10%) corresponding to the two percent (2%) per month from January to May. Otherwise, enforce the corresponding penalty for non-compliance therewith;
iii. Conduct a thorough investigation into the underlying causes of the decline in the number of business permits and license renewals, including potential cases of unreported business closures and enjoin business establishments to settle local taxes, fees, and charges prior to the formal retirement or closure of their operations;
iv. Collect the tax deficiency from the concerned business entities; and
v. Enforce other remedies to ensure that the correct amount of fees and taxes are collected.
b. The Business Permit and Licensing Officer ensure that applicants (i) submit a complete set of all documentary requirements in securing permits and licenses prior to the approval of the Local Chief Executive; and (ii) declare the correct amount of gross sales in their application consistent with the provisions of the Revenue Ordinance.

We recommended that the:
end-user of the goods needed to combat COVID-19 (i) conduct initial scanning of the prevailing prices of drugs, medicines, and medical devices; and (ii) apply DOH issuances on suggested retail price granted to certain goods prior to the preparation of purchase request;
Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) comply with the mandatory documentation of procurement proceedings and ensure that resolutions recommending awards thereafter are reviewed to avoid conflicting details thereon;
Municipal Accountant (i) coordinate with the BAC in the submission of the required documents to the Office of the Auditor for further evaluation; (ii) ensure the completeness of documents before effecting payment to substantiate the regularity of claims; and (iii) prepare a note to disclose in the financial statements the status of the receipt and issuance of in-kind donations; and
Management install an effective and efficient internal control over the receipt and issuance of in-kind donations in conformity with COA Circular Nos. 2014-002 and 2020-009.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive instruct the:
Inventory Committee to conduct a complete physical inventory and submit the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment not later than January 31 of each year;
Acting GSO to (i) maintain Property Cards for each type of properties in coordination with the Office of the Municipal Accountant; (ii) issue the corresponding Acknowledgement Receipt for Equipment (ARE) to fix the accountability of the end-user over the property; and (iii) maintain Local Road Inventory and Road Map and Local Road Network Property Card;
Representative of any office receiving any property from any source to secure all turnover documents or deed of donation from the donor and furnish the Accounting and GSO Office a copy for proper recognition of the same in the books of accounts, simultaneous with the fixing of accountability therefor;
Municipal Engineering Office to provide the Municipal Accountant and the Acting GSO the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects and, on the basis of which, the Municipal Accountant to record the same in the books of accounts;
Municipal Treasurer (or General Services Officer) to take immediate action to ensure that registration and titling of the subject parcel of land in the name of the Municipality is undertaken; and
Municipal Accountant to (i) set up and maintain a lapsing schedule for the PPE items to ensure the accuracy of the periodic depreciation charges for each PPE; (ii) prepare and maintain Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Card (PPELC); (iii) recognize donated properties in the books of accounts; and (iv) prepare Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) to capitalize the titling fees of the seven lots and several capital expenditures, and recognize the depreciation expense and accumulated depreciation related to such assets, if applicable.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to:
instruct the Municipal Planning and Development Officer and Municipal Engineer to (i) ensure that all identified projects will be implemented without further delay; and (ii) continue to monitor and supervise the implementation of projects under the development fund;
direct the Local Development Council to (i) specify the projects, programs and activities under the Development fund; and (ii) stop the practice of lumpsum budgeting and inclusion of generic items in the Annual Investment Plan and Annual Budget, otherwise secure prior authority from the Local Sanggunian;
ensure that all changes in the Annual Investment Program shall be reviewed and endorsed by the Local Development Council;
ensure that any change in the annual budget is supported with valid authority and documentation pursuant to Section 321 of R.A. 7160 and Section 454(2)(b) of its IRR; and
instruct the Municipal Accountant to (i) review the recognition of transactions for Infrastructure Accounts and draw correcting entries therefor; and (ii) reconcile his records with the Municipal Engineer and re-evaluate the nature and intent of expenditures in order to properly recognize all improvements made on various properties in the books of accounts and adjust the cost of PPE when applicable.

