We recommended that the Accounting Office, GSO and Inventory Committee, as the case may be 
(a) prepare and maintain property ledger cards and schedules for the PPE; 
(b) issue ARE for all purchased PPE upon issuance to end-user to establish accountability; 
(c) mobilize additional competent personnel from other departments to facilitate the completion of the physical count of all PPE items and in the event that documents needed to obtain costing of PPE is no longer feasible, consider the fair value thereof as point of reference pursuant to PPSAS 17; 
(d) strengthen the controls on the handling and recording procedures for the PPE by performing a periodic reconciliation of the records of the accounting, the property and actual inventory results; 
(e) set up a spreadsheet application or lapsing schedule for the PPE items to facilitate the computation of  the periodic depreciation and recognition for each PPE item; 
(f) create an appraisal committee for the un-booked parcels of land and record the same under the PPE account; 
(g) exert efforts to secure the necessary documents and reports so that appropriate depreciation can be provided for the PPE accounts, and 
(h) require the Municipal Treasury, Supply Officer and the Municipal Assessor to ascertain the status of parcels of land owned by the agency with titling issues and work for the titling thereof in the name of the Municipality of Minalin,  assuming funds have been provided thereof.

We recommended that the  

a. Municipal Accountant (i) recognize all purchase of supplies stocks under the proper inventory account using the perpetual inventory system; and (ii) recognize supplies consumption monthly based on the SSMI with RIS submitted by the General Services Officer and; 


b. General Services Officer (i) require the preparation of Requisition and Issue Slip (RIS) from end-users to support requisitions and issuance of supplies ; (ii) prepare SSMI supported with RIS for submission to the Municipal Accountant for proper recording; and (iii) conduct periodic inventory of supplies as prescribed by the above regulation.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive 
(a) through the Liga ng mga Barangay, encourage active participation of barangay officials to support the solid waste management program of the government by educating their respective constituents on the proper segregation of reusable or recyclable materials from compostable wastes; 
(b) through the ESMO, comply with the requirements of the law on waste segregation by placing trash bins with proper labels and by collecting only those garbage that are properly segregated; (c) ensure that all barangays had existing and operational MRF; (d) recommend to the Sangguniang Bayan (SB) policies and possible measures that will ensure full compliance by the barangays on the provisions of R.A. No. 9003; (e) initiate the implementation of its Anti-Littering policy ordinances as provided by Section 48 of R.A. No. 9003; (f) completely filled up the Municipal Solid Waste Management Board with officials who could actively perform their respective duties and perform their functions as intended; (g) review every two years or as the need arises the Municipal Solid Waste  Management Plan for the purposes of ensuring its sustainability, viability, effectiveness and relevance in relation to local and international developments in the field of solid waste management (h) provide support to the concerned barangay for the construction of secured fence for the MRF for security, health and sanitation purposes, and  (i) implement  their  plan of issuing Citation Tickets in CY 2017, for violator of the Municipal Environmental Code to strengthens their drive for a more aggressive solid waste management program.

We recommended that the
Municipal Accountant (i) recognize all purchase of supplies stocks under the proper inventory account using the perpetual inventory system; and (ii) recognize supplies consumption monthly based on the SSMI with RIS submitted by the General Services Officer and;
General Services Officer (i) require the preparation of Requisition and Issue Slip (RIS) from end-users to support requisitions and issuance of supplies ; (ii) prepare SSMI supported with RIS for submission to the Municipal Accountant for proper recording; and (iii) conduct periodic inventory of supplies as prescribed by the above regulation.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive require the 

Municipal Accountant to (i) draw the adjusting entry to close the balances of the inventory accounts in the books; (ii) henceforth recognize all purchase of supplies stocks under the proper inventory account ; and (iii) recognize supplies consumption monthly based on the SSMI with RIS submitted by the Treasurer and; 

Municipal Treasurer to (i) require the preparation of Requisition and Issue Slip (RIS) from end-users to support requisitions and issuance of supplies ; (ii) prepare SSMI supported with RIS for submission to the Municipal Accountant for proper recording; and (iii) conduct periodic inventory of supplies as prescribed by the above regulation.

We recommended that the Members of the Local School Board:

prepare a balanced budget with conscious and concerted efforts of observing compliance with the legal and regulatory requirements on SEF budgeting, allocation and utilization and refrain from accommodating expenditures for activities for which the DepEd has the direct mandate to execute;

request for inputs from the DepEd official/School Division Superintendent in the prioritization of SEF projects and expenditures in accordance with the DepEd criteria and with due regard to the provisions of laws, rules and regulations prescribing the limitations on the use of the fund;

maximize the utilization of SEF to attain its objectives, monitor the implementation of the PPAs, and take appropriate actions such as realignment or reprograming, if necessary; and

submit above-cited lacking documents and henceforth, comply with the required documentation for similar transactions.
